Class CaseInsensitiveMap<V>

java.lang.Object
com.github.tommyettinger.ds.ObjectObjectMap<java.lang.CharSequence,​V>
com.github.tommyettinger.ds.CaseInsensitiveMap<V>
All Implemented Interfaces:
java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Iterable<java.util.Map.Entry<java.lang.CharSequence,​V>>, java.util.Map<java.lang.CharSequence,​V>
public class CaseInsensitiveMap<V>
extends ObjectObjectMap<java.lang.CharSequence,​V>
implements java.io.Serializable
A custom variant on ObjectObjectMap that always uses CharSequence keys and compares them as case-insensitive. This uses a fairly complex, somewhat-optimized hashing function because it needs to hash CharSequences rather often, and to do so ignoring case means String.hashCode() won't work, plus not all CharSequences implement hashCode() themselves (such as StringBuilder). User code similar to this can often get away with a simple polynomial hash (the typical Java kind, used by String and Arrays), or if more speed is needed, one with some of these optimizations by Richard Startin.

  • Method Details

    • place

      protected int place​(java.lang.Object item)
      Description copied from class: ObjectObjectMap
      Returns an index >= 0 and <= ObjectObjectMap.mask for the specified item.

      The default behavior uses Fibonacci hashing; it simply gets the Object.hashCode() of item, multiplies it by a specific long constant related to the golden ratio, and makes an unsigned right shift by ObjectObjectMap.shift before casting to int and returning. This can be overridden to hash item differently, though all implementors must ensure this returns results in the range of 0 to ObjectObjectMap.mask, inclusive. If nothing else is changed, then unsigned-right-shifting an int or long by ObjectObjectMap.shift will also restrict results to the correct range.

      Overrides:
      place in class ObjectObjectMap<java.lang.CharSequence,​V>
      Parameters:
      item - a non-null Object; its hashCode() method should be used by most implementations.

    • place

      protected int place​(java.lang.CharSequence item)
      Gets a case-insensitive hash code for the String or other CharSequence item and shifts it so it is between 0 and ObjectObjectMap.mask inclusive. This gets the hash as if all cased letters have been converted to upper case by Character.toUpperCase(char); this should be correct for all alphabets in Unicode except Georgian.
      Parameters:
      item - any non-null CharSequence, such as a String or StringBuilder; will be treated as if it is all upper-case
      Returns:
      a position in the key table where item would be placed; between 0 and ObjectObjectMap.mask inclusive
      "Implementation Note"
      Uses Frost hash, which passes SMHasher's test battery and is fairly fast, at least in C. Frost uses 64-bit math, which behaves reliably but somewhat slowly on GWT, but uses it on usually-small char values. This can't use the built-in pre-calculated hashCode of a String because it's case-sensitive.

    • locateKey

      protected int locateKey​(java.lang.Object key)
      Description copied from class: ObjectObjectMap
      Returns the index of the key if already present, else ~index for the next empty index. This can be overridden to compare for equality differently than Object.equals(Object).

      If source is not easily available and you want to override this, the reference source is: 

       protected int locateKey (Object key) {
                K[] keyTable = this.keyTable;
                for (int i = place(key); ; i = i + 1 & mask) {
                        K other = keyTable[i];
                        if (other == null)
                                return ~i; // Always negative; means empty space is available at i.
                        if (other.equals(key)) // If you want to change how equality is determined, do it here.
                                return i; // Same key was found.
      }
 }
      Overrides:
      locateKey in class ObjectObjectMap<java.lang.CharSequence,​V>
      Parameters:
      key - a non-null Object that should probably be a K
